dred Years War, but closer to home. But while tactics, battles, and logistics have been frequently discussed, the actual experience of being a soldier has been less often studied. Via a careful re-evaluation of original sources, and the use of innovative methodological techniques such as statistical analysis and the use of relational databases, the essays here bring new insights to bear on soldiers, both as individuals and as groups. Topics addressed include military service and the dynamics of recruitment; the social composition of the armies; the question of whether soldiers saw their role as a "profession"; and the experience of prisoners of war. Contributors: Andrew Ayton, David Simpkin, Andrew Spencer, David Bachrach, Iain MacInnes, Adam Chapman, Michael Jones, Guilhem Pepin, Remy Ambuhl, Adrian R. Bell  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMilitary art and sciencexHistoryy14th century. 0aSoldiersxHistoryy14th century. 4aMedieval History. 4aMilitary History. 7aHISTORY / Military / Wars & Conflicts (Other).2bisacsh  aBattle.  aBritish history.  aCavalry.  aFeudalism.  aHundred Years War.  aInfantry.  aMedieval life.  aMedieval soldier.  aMedieval troops.  aMedieval warfare.  aMedieval.  aMiddle ages.  aMilitary force.  aMilitary history.  aPrisoners of war.  aRecruitment.  afourteenth century.1 aAmbühl, Rémy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAyton, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBachrach, David S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBachrach, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBell, Adrian R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBell, Adrian R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/re